## A Memory Budget Problem

Imagine you're deploying a language model. It has 24 layers, 16 attention heads, embedding dimension 1536, and you want to support 2048-token conversations. During inference, you cache every token's K and V projections (we'll learn why in notebook 20).

How much memory does that take?

```elixir
n_layers = 24
n_heads = 16
head_dim = 96
seq_len = 2048
bytes_per_float = 2

kv_bytes = n_layers * 2 * n_heads * seq_len * head_dim * bytes_per_float
kv_mb = Float.round(kv_bytes / (1024 * 1024), 1)
kv_gb = Float.round(kv_bytes / (1024 * 1024 * 1024), 2)

IO.puts("KV cache per user session:")
IO.puts("  #{n_layers} layers x 2 (K+V) x #{n_heads} heads x #{seq_len} tokens x #{head_dim} dims x #{bytes_per_float} bytes")
IO.puts("  = #{kv_mb} MB (#{kv_gb} GB)")
IO.puts("")
IO.puts("Serve 10 users simultaneously: #{Float.round(kv_gb * 10, 1)} GB just for KV caches.")
IO.puts("That's more than many GPUs have!")
```

In 2019, **Noam Shazeer** — one of the eight authors of the original "Attention Is All You Need" paper (2017) — had a radical idea. He noticed the bottleneck during inference wasn't compute. It was memory bandwidth: loading K and V from memory for every head at every step.

His solution: **what if all query heads shared a single set of K and V?** Instead of 16 separate K/V projections, just use one. He called it Multi-Query Attention (MQA).

It worked — inference speed doubled. But quality dropped noticeably.

Four years later, in 2023, Joshua Ainslie at Google Research found the sweet spot: instead of 1 K/V head or 16 K/V heads, use something in between. **Grouped-Query Attention (GQA)** was published at EMNLP 2023, and it's now the default in LLaMA 3, Mistral, and Gemma 2.

## Math Notation

| Formula | Meaning | Elixir | Nx |
|---------|---------|--------|----|
| `n_h` | Number of Q heads | `n_head` | `n_head` |
| `n_kv` | Number of K/V heads (≤ n_h) | `n_kv_head` | `n_kv_head` |
| `r = n_h / n_kv` | Repeat factor for GQA | `div(n_head, n_kv_head)` | `div(n_head, n_kv_head)` |
| `W_Q`, `W_K`, `W_V` | Separate Q/K/V projections | (weight matrices) | `c_q`, `c_k`, `c_v` |
| `QK_norm` | Normalize Q and K before dot product | (apply rms_norm) | `rms_norm(q)`, `rms_norm(k)` |
| `w` | Sliding window size | `window_size` | `window_size` |

